 - The hardware stack (RISC-V)
+  - Software runs on hardware
+  - Free Software has been around for a long time, but from the very beginning the CPUs it ran have been non-free
+  - As a result, for decades, there has been a constant fight by OSS advocates to get Linux support for things
+  - On x86, vendors (e.g. Intel/AMD) eventually stepped up and started supporting Linux
+  - x86 isn't very competitive though outside of the desktop, there is in practice a duopoly between Intel and AMD
+  - On mobile, the situation is far worse - Android phones usually never get proper mainline Linux support and it's almost impossible to replace the software running on them nowadways
+  - Even if you replace the software running on there, you're living on borrowed time since Google etc. have made it very clear that they see this as a feature, not as a bug, and modern ARM CPUs are more and more locked down with control systems (e.g. HSMs and FUSES that blow when you unlock the bootloader) embedded into the silicon itself
+  - That makes it extremely hard to get mainline Linux on phones or anything other than a desktop computer or server
+  - Thankfully, RISC-V now exists and is a way out of this
+  - Fully open-source, standardized, simple and very competitive instruction set
+  - Originally from UC Berkeley, now managed by a Swiss foundation
+  - Just reached 25% market share in 2026, mostly driven by IoT but more and more also by mobile, desktop and servers
+  - RISC-V is very adaptable and extensible, but a new "minimum common denominator" (a profile, RV23) has been accepted recently that's the first one with enough features (vectors, hypervisor extension etc.) that's genuinely competitive with ARM and x86 performance-wise
+  - I've got a RISC-V system with me today, but we are at an inflection point with the first RV23 chips now shipping (SpacemiT K3)
+  - Even the IP itself is completely open for the leading-edge CPUs (e.g. XiangShan) - anyone with access to a fab can make the chips now, or design their own ones
+  - The RISC-V vendors, esp. DeepComputing/SpacemiT have been much better than ARM about mainline Linux support, and the specifications around the system (e.g. OpenSBI) are much more friendly to open systems than ARM and x86
+  - Combined with much better x86 emulation tooling (box86 etc.) and PCIe support from day 1 (via the OSS AMD drivers), soon, we might be free from having to use proprietary instructions sets to get great performance
 - Analog Twin: Keeping pen and paper offices alive for resilience
   - More and more institutions are moving to fully digital-only/"paperless" operations
   - Backup systems exist, but are increasingly brittle and usually depend on some form of internet to exist

